<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-21T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="63" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d63">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee/34:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Acting Chairman of the American Delegation
                                        (<persName corresp="#p_GHS1" type="from">Gibson</persName>)
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-21T17:00:00+01:00">April
                                        21, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received April 21—2 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>139. Considerable interest is attached to the meeting of the General
                                Commission this morning owing to the presence of <persName corresp="#p_MJR1">MacDonald</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BH2">Bruening</persName>.</p>
                            <pb facs="0220" n="100" xml:id="pg_100"/>
                            <p>The former took occasion during a translation to make a personal
                                appeal to <persName corresp="#p_PJ2">Paul-Boncour</persName> in an
                                informal conversation urging him to abandon his opposition to the
                                British resolution telling him that the world was weary with the
                                bickerings at Geneva over words and that he thought that it might
                                help restore the confidence that was nearly lost in the proceedings
                                here if the French would join in the support of a resolution for
                                which there seemed to be such general agreement.</p>
                            <p>
                                <persName corresp="#p_PJ2">Paul-Boncour</persName> felt, however,
                                that he was unable to respond to <persName corresp="#p_MJR1">MacDonald</persName>’s reasoning.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GHS1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>